01:37:56.580 --> 01:38:02.840
we used system, a
multispectral imaging system

01:38:02.840 --> 01:38:06.450
that we've made built
in our lab.

01:38:06.450 --> 01:38:13.410
And it's a way to collect the
light reflected by the violin,

01:38:13.410 --> 01:38:18.740
using a system which is better
than a simple red, green,

01:38:18.740 --> 01:38:21.270
blue camera with three channels.

01:38:21.270 --> 01:38:26.400
We used a 14 channel color
camera, if you want to say.

01:38:26.400 --> 01:38:31.580
And this allows -- so you
see here this the 14 bandpass

01:38:31.580 --> 01:38:38.040
of the 14 filters and we collect
a series, a stack of 14 images,

01:38:38.040 --> 01:38:42.130
each of them corresponding
to a very narrow band

01:38:42.130 --> 01:38:47.580
in the visible regions
of the spectrum.

01:38:47.580 --> 01:38:53.580
And this process allows to
measure the reflected light,

01:38:53.580 --> 01:38:58.560
properly emitted
reflected by the object.

01:38:58.560 --> 01:39:00.380
It's not exactly a
color measurement.

01:39:00.380 --> 01:39:02.650
It's a measurement
of the reflectance.

01:39:02.650 --> 01:39:06.560
It's related but
it's not the same.

01:39:06.560 --> 01:39:10.730
And we did some comparison
in one of the band.

01:39:10.730 --> 01:39:15.880
So we picked this band in the
yellow area, in the yellow area

01:39:15.880 --> 01:39:19.090
of the visible spectrum
just to show it to you.

01:39:19.090 --> 01:39:22.040
But we could have
picked the other bands

01:39:22.040 --> 01:39:24.890
like in the spectral region.

01:39:24.890 --> 01:39:29.620
The idea is, was
to subtract the --

01:39:29.620 --> 01:39:32.180
to make a subtraction

01:39:32.180 --> 01:39:36.880
like between what is now
the instruments looking

01:39:36.880 --> 01:39:40.490
like minus what was the
instrument looking like before,

01:39:40.490 --> 01:39:44.640
using this multispectral
reflectance imaging.

01:39:44.640 --> 01:39:47.670
And it allows -- so
there is a false color --

01:39:47.670 --> 01:39:51.750
so there is a quite heavy
foil for me at least.

01:39:51.750 --> 01:39:53.930
My colleagues are very expert

01:39:53.930 --> 01:39:59.240
on that data processing
data correction,

01:39:59.240 --> 01:40:00.900
so that you can subtract.

01:40:00.900 --> 01:40:05.990
And you see the fourth color,
the pink area, shows to you

01:40:05.990 --> 01:40:11.960
where there is more reflected
light emitted after a treatment

01:40:11.960 --> 01:40:16.140
than before treatment
in the yellow region.

01:40:16.140 --> 01:40:22.500
And it's a way to very
properly document and map

01:40:22.500 --> 01:40:25.250
where material has been removed.

01:40:25.250 --> 01:40:27.000
Where color -- sorry.

01:40:27.000 --> 01:40:30.610
I said color and its color
scientists will not be happy

01:40:30.610 --> 01:40:32.730
if I say that.

01:40:32.730 --> 01:40:35.000
Where more light is reflected

01:40:35.000 --> 01:40:37.150
from the instrument
in the yellow region.

01:40:37.150 --> 01:40:39.670
So basically where
it was very dark,

01:40:39.670 --> 01:40:42.610
now it's brighter in the yellow.

01:40:42.610 --> 01:40:44.290
I'm showing only the
yellow but we can do

01:40:44.290 --> 01:40:46.360
that for all the spectrum.

01:40:46.360 --> 01:40:51.550
And you see there was
obviously a gain in brightness

01:40:51.550 --> 01:40:55.000
in the central region but
also, I don't know if you see

01:40:55.000 --> 01:40:59.570
that on the screen, but
this little badly restored

01:40:59.570 --> 01:41:02.420
in the past, maybe in
the 19th century crack,

01:41:02.420 --> 01:41:09.470
was a colored retouch that was
not well and we make it lighter.

01:41:09.470 --> 01:41:12.360
So now it's a brighter area.

01:41:12.360 --> 01:41:16.050
And dirt in this area
has been cleaned and here

01:41:16.050 --> 01:41:17.950
in this corner it has
