01:45:13.410 --> 01:45:17.660
It's changing too much.

01:45:17.660 --> 01:45:22.650
Third, I'm showing you another
technique, quite experimental

01:45:22.650 --> 01:45:27.190
that has been developed by
our colleagues in [inaudible]

01:45:27.190 --> 01:45:30.710
which is in Paris University.

01:45:30.710 --> 01:45:34.630
And this tool is part
of the acoustics field

01:45:34.630 --> 01:45:37.550
and the vibrations field.

01:45:37.550 --> 01:45:42.380
You imagine you see
on the top a side view

01:45:42.380 --> 01:45:44.480
of an array of microphones.

01:45:44.480 --> 01:45:50.510
These are 128 microphone in
an array, in a grid matrix.

01:45:50.510 --> 01:45:55.480
And they record sound
all at the same time.

01:45:55.480 --> 01:45:57.580
They are synchronized.

01:45:57.580 --> 01:46:02.970
So you collect on 128
channels simultaneously.

01:46:02.970 --> 01:46:07.280
The acoustic answer
and the microphone.

01:46:07.280 --> 01:46:09.450
So we don't play
the violin here.

01:46:09.450 --> 01:46:12.110
We will not bow on
the instrument.

01:46:12.110 --> 01:46:16.980
It's a tool to again look at
the way the soundboard vibrates

01:46:16.980 --> 01:46:19.130
and how the instrument vibrates.

01:46:19.130 --> 01:46:27.700
The experiment, you need to make
a little impact with a triggered

01:46:27.700 --> 01:46:30.430
by computer -- a hammer
triggered by computer.

01:46:30.430 --> 01:46:33.210
So you know where --
when it's triggered

01:46:33.210 --> 01:46:35.510
and you synchronize
the sound collection

01:46:35.510 --> 01:46:38.320
of the 128 microscope.

01:46:38.320 --> 01:46:42.840
And this is giving you what
is called the near field

01:46:42.840 --> 01:46:44.690
acoustic holography.

01:46:44.690 --> 01:46:45.990
So it's giving you data

01:46:45.990 --> 01:46:49.440
of the air pressure
modification of the mics.

01:46:49.440 --> 01:46:52.170
But it tells you how
the soundboard vibrates.

01:46:52.170 --> 01:46:56.140
And if there is a crack in
the soundboard, you will see

01:46:56.140 --> 01:47:00.210
in the answer of the
machine of the technique.

01:47:00.210 --> 01:47:06.520
So this is a very important
mechanical monitoring tool.

01:47:06.520 --> 01:47:09.890
And here I'm showing
the radiated pressure,

01:47:09.890 --> 01:47:11.190
some pressure.

01:47:11.190 --> 01:47:16.140
It's an average on
the 128 microphones.

01:47:16.140 --> 01:47:22.670
And the x-axis is the frequency
in hertz and you have modes

01:47:22.670 --> 01:47:25.570
of vibration of the
soundboard which are appearing

01:47:25.570 --> 01:47:28.600
as peaks in the spectrum.

01:47:28.600 --> 01:47:32.340
I'm not a specialist
of this field

01:47:32.340 --> 01:47:35.880
with my colleagues [inaudible]
our colleagues at [inaudible]

01:47:35.880 --> 01:47:40.630
who are the experts on that.

01:47:40.630 --> 01:47:46.020
But we evidence quite important
and noticeable differences

01:47:46.020 --> 01:47:51.130
in the vibration mode between
the before the treatment

01:47:51.130 --> 01:47:52.910
and after the treatment.

01:47:52.910 --> 01:47:56.860
So this is currently
investigated

01:47:56.860 --> 01:48:01.200
